  "summary": "Multiplying a polynomial by a monomial uses the distributive property: multiply the monomial by each term of the polynomial. For each multiplication, multiply coefficients and add exponents of like variables. The result will have the same number of terms as the original polynomial (unless like terms appear after combining multiple products). This operation is used in simplifying expressions and in geometry for finding areas of figures with variable dimensions. Common errors include forgetting to multiply all terms, exponent mistakes, and sign errors. Mastering monomial-polynomial multiplication is essential for more complex polynomial operations, including multiplying binomials and higher-degree polynomials.",

